{
  "answer": "In \"Soul and Body II,\" an Old English elegy, the soul returns to its former body every seven nights for three hundred winters (or until Doomsday) and bitterly rebukes it for a lifetime of sinful indulgence that has doomed the soul to hellish torment.[^1] The soul's direct speech to the corpse—described as \"dust,\" \"filth of the earth,\" \"food for worms,\" and a \"flesh-hoard\"—accuses the body of pride, gluttony, and lust; of ignoring the soul's spiritual thirst for God while prioritizing fleshly pleasures; and of preparing hell for the soul despite God's gift of it from heaven and redemption through Christ's blood.[^2][^3] The soul foretells the body's postmortem decay by worms, its worthlessness even to kin, and mutual suffering at judgment, when the body must answer for both their sins: \"what shall we two do, when He has joined us again a second time? Then we must together forever endure such miseries as you prescribed for us.\"[^4]\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, \"Soul and Body II\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/10-soul-and-body-ii/translation/#p-34bcc7).\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, \"Soul and Body II\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/10-soul-and-body-ii/translation/#p-34bcc7).\n[^3]: *Old English Elegies*, \"Soul and Body II\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/10-soul-and-body-ii/translation/#p-00ea0f).\n[^4]: *Old English Elegies*, \"Soul and Body II\" [paragraph](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/10-soul-and-body-ii/translation/#p-7f7247).",
